Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Pour the boiling water from your kettle and @salt{1/2%tsp} into a large #saucepan{} and bring back to the boil. Once boiling, add the @linguine{200%g} to the saucepan of boiling water and cook for ~{12%minutes}. When cooked, drain in a #colander{}, return to the pan off the heat and drizzle with a little @oil{a little} to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a large #frying pan{} on high heat (no oil). When hot, add the @lamb mince{200%g}. Cook until browned, ~{3-4%mins}. Break it up with a #spoon{} as it cooks. 

> Tip: Carefully pour away any excess fat if desired!

Sprinkle over the @dried Italian herbs{1/2%tsp} and cook, stirring, for another ~{1%minute}. Meanwhile, trim the @courgette{1} then quarter length-ways. Chop width-ways into small pieces.

Add the @Worcester sauce{1%tbsp} to the lamb and allow to bubble away until evaporated. Stir in the courgette, @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1%28g tin}, @red wine stock paste{1%tbsp} and a pinch of @?sugar{pinch}, bring to the boil.

Reduce the heat to medium and simmer until the sauce is thick and tomatoey, ~{5-6%mins}.

> Tip: Add a splash of pasta water if it gets too thick.

Toss the drained linguine through the sauce along with half the @hard Italian style cheese{40%g}(grated) and cook until piping hot. Taste and season with @salt and @pepper if needed.

Serve the lamb linguine in #bowls{} finished with a sprinkle of the remaining hard Italian cheese. Enjoy!

> Looking for a quick and tasty midweek dinner option? Try cooking up our Lamb Linguine with Courgette in just 20 minutes for a delicious and speedy meal.